web_results.snippet: Lupinus, commonly known as lupin, lupine, or regionally bluebonnet, is a genus of plants in the legume family Fabaceae. The genus includes over 199 species, with centers of diversity in North and South America. Smaller centers occur in North Africa and the Mediterranean.

related_questions.question: Do lupines come back every year?
related_questions.snippet: The most important thing to note before planting Lupines, is that they are available as both annuals and perennials. While Lupine seeds may yield both annual (life cycle complete in one growing season) and perennial (long-lived, coming back each spring) varieties, potted Lupine plants are typically perennial cultivars.
related_questions.title: How To Grow Lupines | American Meadows

related_questions.question: Do lupines bloom all summer?
related_questions.snippet: Depending on the variety and your zone, lupine flowers will bloom from late spring through the first weeks of July. As a result, we recommend planting them with some late-blooming, summertime favorites — zinnia, rudbeckia, daisies — to keep the color going well into fall.
related_questions.title: Complete Guide to Plant, Grow and Care for Lupine Flowers

related_questions.question: Do lupine spread?
related_questions.snippet: Individual lupines plants do not spread. As they get older the root gets bigger and sends up more flower stalks. Lupines, do, however, produce dozens of pealike seeds per plant, which are dispersed when the pods pop open in late July or early August.
related_questions.title: Snakeroot Organic Farm's Lupines

related_questions.question: Where do lupines grow best?
related_questions.snippet: Lupins do best in full sun or dappled shade, in moist but well-drained soil. Like many other perennials with tall flowers, lupins benefit from a sheltered position.
related_questions.title: How to Grow Lupins | BBC Gardeners World Magazine

answer_box.title: Lupine Definition & Meaning - Merriam-Webster
answer_box.snippet: Lupine comes from lupus, Latin for "wolf", and its related adjective lupinus, "wolfish". Lupine groups have a highly organized social structure, with leaders and followers clearly distinguished; dogs, since they're descended from wolves, often show these lupine patterns when living in groups.

buttons.subtitle: How To Grow Lupine
buttons.title: How to Plant and Grow Lupine - Better Homes & Gardens
buttons.snippet: To plant lupine seeds outdoors, prepare a bed by scratching the soil. Scarify the seeds, plant them 1/4-inch into the soil, and barely cover them. Keep the soil moist until you see germination, and continue to water regularly until the plant is established. Most plants flower more profusely in their second season.

buttons.subtitle: When Do Lupines Grow
buttons.title: Lupine Flower Guide: How to Grow and Care for Lupine Flowers - 2024
buttons.snippet: Lupines thrive best in USDA hardiness zones four through eight, and should be planted in the late spring or early fall for winter germination, which means that your flowers will bloom between late spring and mid-summer. They can also be planted in the early spring for later bloom times.

buttons.subtitle: Lupines Sun Or Shade
buttons.title: How To Grow Lupines | American Meadows
buttons.snippet: Light: Full sun is preferred. Lupine can grow in part shade, but flowering will be lessened. Soil: Lupine needs well-draining soil above all else. They prefer soil on the acid side and will not tolerate high levels of alkalinity or water-logged conditions.

buttons.title: How to Grow and Care for Lupine (Bluebonnet) - The Spruce
buttons.snippet: Plant lupines during cooler early spring or fall temperatures. Use loose, sandy soil for lupines, and avoid planting this flower in clay soil unless it is amended. Offer lupines more sun and minimum shade. Space smaller lupines a foot apart and larger ones 2 to 3 feet apart.

buttons.subtitle: Is Lupine Edible?
buttons.title: Growing edible lupins - Garden Organic
buttons.snippet: Like other legumes, lupins should be soaked overnight, then boiled for an hour before using them in a recipe. They can then be used in stews, salads, burgers or ground up into 'lupin hummus'. Lupins can also be ground into a flour which can be made into cakes and pancakes .
